The F-word in the dictionary
The F-word was recorded in a dictionary in 1598 (John Florio‚Äôs A Worlde of Wordes, London: Arnold Hatfield for Edw. Blount). It is remotely derived from the Latin futuere and Old German ficken/fucken meaning ‚Äòto strike or penetrate‚Äô, which had the slang meaning to copulate. Eric Partridge, a famous etymologist, said that the German word was related to the Latin words for pugilist, puncture, and prick. One folk etymology claims that it derives from ‚Äúfor unlawful carnal knowledge,‚Äù but this has been debunked by etymologists.
